Inheritance:
Single Inheritance:
One child class inherits one parent class
class A {}
class B extends A {}
Example:
class Employee {
    name: string = "Ravi";

    work() {
        console.log("Employee is working");
    }
}
class Manager extends Employee {
    manageTeam() {
        console.log("Manager manages the team");
    }
}
let m = new Manager();
m.work();
m.manageTeam();  #manager automatically gets all employee features
Output:
Employee is working
Manager manages the team

Multilevel Inheritance:
Inheritance in different levels
class A{}
class B extends A{}
class C extends B{}
Example:
class Employee {
    work() {
        console.log("Employee works on tasks");
    }
}
class Manager extends Employee {
    manageTeam() {
        console.log("Manager manages employees");
    }
}

class Director extends Manager {
    makeStrategy() {
        console.log("Director creates company strategy");
    }
}
let d = new Director();
d.work();
d.manageTeam();
d.makeStrategy();
Output:
Employee works on tasks
Manager manages employees
Director creates company strategy

Hierarchial Inheritance:
Multiple classes inherit from the same parent class
class A{}
class B extends A{}
class C extends A{}
Example:
class Vehicle {
    start() {
        console.log("Vehicle starts");
    }
}
class Car extends Vehicle {
    drive() {
        console.log("Car is driving");
    }
}
class Bike extends Vehicle {
    ride() {
        console.log("Bike is riding");
    }
}
let car = new Car();
car.start();
car.drive();
let bike = new Bike();
bike.start();
bike.ride();
Different vehicle types share common vehicle features
Output:
Vehicle starts
Car is driving
Vehicle starts
Bike is riding

Multiple Inheritance:
One class can implement multiple interfaces
example:
interface Camera {
    takePhoto(): void;  # the method doesnot return any value
}

interface MusicPlayer {
    playMusic(): void;
}

class SmartPhone implements Camera, MusicPlayer {

    takePhoto() {
        console.log("Taking photo");
    }

    playMusic() {
        console.log("Playing music");
    }
}

let phone = new SmartPhone();
phone.takePhoto();
phone.playMusic();
Output:
Taking photo
Playing music
smartphone class inherits features from multiple interfaces

Property,Methods and constructor:
Property:
variables inside a class
Method:
Functions inside a class
Constructor:
 A constructor is a special method automatically called when an object is created
Example:
class Employee {

    name: string;
    salary: number;

    constructor(name: string, salary: number) {
        this.name = name;
        this.salary = salary;
    }

    display() {
        console.log("Name:", this.name);
        console.log("Salary:", this.salary);
    }
}

let emp1 = new Employee("Ravi", 50000);
emp1.display();
Output:
Name: Ravi
Salary: 50000

Access Modifiers in Typescript:
It control the visibility of class members
Public
Private
Protected
Public:
Accessible everywhere
class Student {

    public name: string;

    constructor(name: string) {
        this.name = name;
    }

    display() {
        console.log(this.name);
    }
}

let s = new Student("Ravi");
console.log(s.name);   // Accessible outside class
s.display();
Output:
Ravi
Ravi
Private:
private members are accessible only inside the class.
class BankAccount {
    private balance: number;
    constructor(balance: number) {
        this.balance = balance;
    }
    showBalance() {
        console.log("Balance:", this.balance);
    }
}
let account = new BankAccount(5000);
account.showBalance();

// console.log(account.balance); ❌ Error
Output:
Balance: 5000
Balance: 5000

Protected:
protected members are accessible:
✔ Inside the class
✔ In child classes (inheritance)
❌ Not accessible outside the class

class Employee {
     protected salary: number = 50000;
}

class Manager extends Employee {
   displaySalary() {
        console.log(this.salary);
    }
}
let m = new Manager();
m.displaySalary();

// console.log(m.salary); ❌ Error
Output:
50000

Static Methods in TypeScript
A static method belongs to the class, not to the object.
It is called using the class name.

Example
class MathUtils {

    static add(a: number, b: number): number {
        return a + b;
    }
}
console.log(MathUtils.add(5, 3));
